# File Structure Rules

## Route groups
- `(marketing)/` — Public pages. No auth required. Uses site header + footer layout.
- `(auth)/` — Auth pages. Centered layout. No sidebar.
- `(dashboard)/` — Agency owner workspace. Requires auth. Has sidebar.
- `(builder)/` — Fullscreen GrapesJS editor. No nav, no sidebar.
- `(admin)/` — Super admin only. Separate sidebar with admin nav.
- `[tenant]/` — Dynamic. Served to agency's subdomain. Completely separate UI.

## Feature folder pattern (ALWAYS follow this)
When adding a new feature under a route group:
```
feature-name/
├── page.tsx              ← Server component, data fetching here
├── loading.tsx           ← Suspense fallback (skeleton UI)
├── error.tsx             ← Error boundary ('use client')
├── _components/          ← Components used ONLY by this feature
│   ├── feature-form.tsx
│   └── feature-card.tsx
├── _hooks/               ← Custom hooks for this feature
│   └── use-feature.ts
└── [id]/                 ← Sub-routes if needed
    └── page.tsx
```

## When to put a component where
- Used in ONE feature only → `feature/_components/`
- Used in MULTIPLE features in the same app → `src/components/`
- Used in MULTIPLE apps (future) → `packages/ui/`

## Naming conventions
- Feature folders: `kebab-case`
- Private folders: `_prefix` (prevents Next.js from treating as routes)
- Route groups: `(group-name)` (invisible in URL)
- Dynamic routes: `[param]` or `[...slug]` for catch-all

## Server vs Client components
- `page.tsx` files → always Server Components
- `layout.tsx` files → always Server Components (unless need context)
- `_components/` files → Server Components unless they have interactivity
- `_hooks/` files → always `'use client'`
- `store/` files → always `'use client'`
